article.headline: Schreiber has third big game against Baylor
article.linkText: Texas' Schreiber again torments Baylor with 23 points
article.story:
WACO, Texas (AP) -- The best seems to come out in Heather Schreiber when Texas plays Baylor.

She tied her season high with 23 points, and grabbed nine rebounds to lead the 10th-ranked Longhorns (20-5, 13-1 Big 12) to a 79-57 victory over the Lady Bears (17-9, 6-8 Big 12).

Schreiber also scored 23 points last month in a 70-50 victory
over Baylor and set her career high of 28 points last season
against the Lady Bears.

"I really didn't think I would get that many opportunities
tonight after what I did last time,'' she said. "But we reversed
the ball very well and knocked down our shots.''

   Schreiber connected on nine of 15 shots, including three-of-four
3-pointers. As a team, the Longhorns were nine of 13 on 3-pointers.

"This team can shoot the ball,'' Texas coach Jody Conradt said.
"One stat that stands out tonight is our 23 assists. When you get
good ball movement and get into the flow of the game, it sets up a
lot of good three-point looks.''

   Steffanie Blackmon led Baylor with 20 points. Jamie Carey added
15 points and Kala Bowers contributed 13.

Texas scored 15 points in the first three minutes of the second
half, hitting all three of its 3-pointers to take a 53-33 lead.
Carey scored six points in the outburst with a pair of 3-pointers,
and Bowers added five points in the 15-6 run.

The Lady Bears closed to 53-38, but Texas continued its
long-range onslaught, and back-to-back 3-pointers by Schreiber and
Carey gave the Longhorns a 65-42 lead with just under 11 minutes
left to play.

"This Texas team could have beaten a lot of folks tonight,''
Baylor coach Kim Mulkey-Robertson said. "Their perimeter game has
brought them so much more than they had last year, and everybody
looks to score.''

Trailing 13-12 midway through the first half, the Longhorns scored seven straight points and went in front 19-13 with Schreiber's five points keying the run.

The Lady Bears closed to 21-18 on a 3-pointer by Jordan Davis, but Texas countered with baskets by Tai Dillard and Nina Norman and took a 25-18 lead with just over seven minutes remaining. The Longhorns extended their margin to 38-27 at the half.
